{{Coord|43|44|4.74|N|7|25|16.8|E|scale:1563_type:landmark_region:MC|display=title}} {{Infobox Grand Prix race report |Type = F1 |Country = Monaco |Grand Prix = Monaco |Image = Circuit de Monaco 1976.png |Official name = |Date = May 31 |Year = 1981 |Race_No = 6 |Season_No = 15 |Location = [[Circuit de Monaco]] |Course = Street circuit |Course_mi = 2.057 |Course_km = 3.312 |Distance_laps = 76 |Distance_mi = 156.406 |Distance_km = 251.712 |Weather = Dry |Pole_Driver = [[Nelson Piquet]] |Pole_Team = [[Brabham]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] |Pole_Time = 1:25.710 |Pole_Country = Brazil |pole_flag_suffix = 1968 |Fast_Driver = [[Alan Jones (Formula 1)|Alan Jones]] |Fast_Team = [[WilliamsF1|Williams]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] |Fast_Time = 1:27.47 |Fast_Lap = 48 |Fast_Country = Australia |First_Driver = [[Gilles Villeneuve]] |First_Team = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] |First_Country = Canada |Second_Driver = [[Alan Jones (Formula 1)|Alan Jones]] |Second_Team = [[WilliamsF1|Williams]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] |Second_Country = Australia |Third_Driver = [[Jacques Laffite]] |Third_Team = [[Equipe Ligier|Ligier]]-[[Equipe Matra Sports|Matra]] |Third_Country = France }} [[File:Piquetmonaco.jpg|250px|thumb|right|[[Nelson Piquet]] in a [[Brabham BT49|Brabham BT49C]]]] The '''1981 Monaco Grand Prix''' was a [[Formula One]] [[motor race]] held at [[Circuit de Monaco|Monaco]] on May 31, 1981.
==Race== The start of the race was delayed after a fire in the Loews Hotel kitchens, which necessitated the fire service pumping large quantities of water to put the fires out. Water then seeped through the floors of the hotel and into the tunnel, delaying the race for an hour. [[Nelson Piquet]] led for much of the race, but crashed out late on. New race leader Alan Jones then suffered a fuel feed problem in the latter stages of the race, allowing [[Gilles Villeneuve]] in his [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]], to take his first victory since 1979. Championship leader [[Carlos Reutemann]] retired with gearbox problems, breaking a 15-race streak of consistently finishing in the points.
