{{notability|Organizations|date=March 2015}}


The '''Pan Africa Chemistry Network''' (PACN) connects chemists across [[Africa]].<ref name=Scidev>{{cite web|title=African chemistry booming, but funding is scarce|url=http://www.scidev.net/global/indigenous/news/african-chemistry-booming-but-funding-is-scarce.html|publisher=SciDev|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> It was launched in [[London]] on 21 November 2007 and in [[Nairobi]] on 27 May 2008 by the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]].<ref name=PACN1>{{cite web|title=Pan Africa Chemistry Network|url=http://www.rsc.org/Membership/Networking/InternationalActivities/PanAfrica/|publisher=Royal Society of Chemistry|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> The PACN works to connect [[Chemist|chemists]] across Africa and has five centres of excellence in [[analytical chemistry]] in [[Kenya]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Ghana]] and [[Nigeria]].<ref name=CAA />

The aim of the PACN is:<ref name=CAA>{{cite web|title=Chemistry across Africa|url=http://www.rsc.org/news-events/rsc-news/features/2014/sep/chemistry-across-africa/|publisher=Royal Society of Chemistry|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref>

{{quote|To enable a self-sustaining science base in Africa and to enhance the number of skilled scientists in Africa through networking, skills development and knowledge creation to support an increase in scientific output and its application to challenges.}}

In partnership with [[Syngenta]], who donated £1 million over five years three PACN Centres of Excellence in Analytical Chemistry were established in Kenya, Ghana and Ethiopia.<ref name="Syngenta Water">{{cite web|title=PACN Sustainable water conference|url=http://www.syngenta.com/global/corporate/en/news-center/events-and-presentations/Pages/pacn2009.aspx|website=Syngenta|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>

Since December 2011, [[Procter & Gamble]] have been working with the PACN and leading scientists and students to exchange knowledge, enhance skills and generate opportunities for innovation in the areas of hygiene, health and waste management. A Collaboration Lab at the [[University of Lagos]] in Nigeria was established which includes provision of analytical equipment and internships for Nigerian scientists to apply their knowledge to real life industry challenge.<ref name="P&G PACN">{{cite web|title=P&G Announces Partnership with PACN, UNILAG|url=http://www.thisdaylive.com/articles/p-g-announces-partnership-with-pacn-unilag/161060/|website=This Day Live article|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>

The PACN organises a number of events including an annual congress, [[GC-MS]] training<ref name=KNUST>{{cite web|title=PACN GC-MS Workshop|url=https://www.knust.edu.gh/news/news-items/pan-african-chemistry-network-holds-workshop|website=KNUST Ghana|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> and scientific symposia.<ref name=PACNweb>{{cite web|title=Past Events|url=http://www.panafricachemistrynetwork.com/Past_Events.html|publisher=Pan Africa Chemistry Network|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref>

